  "prompt": "Can I use any image from google/website in my blog, along with mentioning the credits for the image?",
  "response": "Using images from Google or any website in your blog requires careful consideration of copyright laws and usage rights. Here are some important points to keep in mind:\n\n1. **Copyright**: Most images found online are protected by copyright, which means you cannot use them without permission from the copyright owner, even if you credit the source.\n\n2. **Creative Commons Licenses**: Some images are available under Creative Commons licenses, which allow you to use them under certain conditions (such as providing attribution). Be sure to check the specific terms of the license; some may not allow modifications or commercial use.\n\n3. **Stock Images**: Consider using stock photo websites that provide images for a fee or for free under specific usage conditions (e.g., Unsplash, Pexels, or Shutterstock). Always check the licensing agreements for each image.\n\n4. **Public Domain**: Images that are in the public domain can be used freely without permission or attribution. Websites like Pixabay or Wikimedia Commons often have collections of public domain images.\n\n5. **Attribution**: Even when using images that allow it, proper attribution is important. Follow the guidelines provided by the image source for how to credit the creator.\n\nIn short, it\u2019s best to avoid using any image from the internet without verifying its copyright status and permissions. If in doubt, seek images from sources that explicitly allow usage.",
